<#
.SYNOPSIS
    CyberArk Privilege Cloud - Full Dashboard Data Export Pipeline
.DESCRIPTION
    Pulls Platforms, Safes, Safe Members, Accounts, Account Activities (usage),
    and (best-effort) License Usage from the CyberArk Privilege Cloud REST API,
    and writes them as CSVs for Power BI to consume. Feeds these dashboard reports:
      - Platform Standard KPI report      (Platforms.csv)
      - Safe Standard KPI report          (Safes.csv, SafeMembers.csv)
      - Used Account Usage Details report (AccountActivities.csv)
      - License Procured vs Used report   (LicenseUsage.csv - best effort, see NOTES)
      - Account Onboarded vs Used report  (Accounts.csv + AccountActivities.csv + Summary.csv)
.Mode
    READ-ONLY. Every CyberArk API call in this script is a GET. The ONLY POST
    is the OAuth2 client-credentials token request. No retrieve/change/verify/
    reconcile/add/delete endpoints are ever called.
.Outputs
    <RootFolder>\Latest\    - current run's CSVs, run.log, manifest.json (Power BI points here)
    <RootFolder>\Archive\<timestamp>\ - previous run's files, moved here before each new run
.NOTES
    Author   : Mohan C
    Requires : PowerShell 5.1+ (also runs on PowerShell 7+)
    Schema caveat: CyberArk's exact JSON field names for Platform config detail
    and the License Usage report were not fully confirmed against a live tenant
    at authoring time. This script flattens nested JSON generically (see
    ConvertTo-FlatObject) so unexpected/extra fields still land in the CSV as
    their own columns instead of breaking the export - inspect the first run's
    Platforms.csv / LicenseUsage.csv column headers and adjust the "candidate
    field name" arrays below if compliance columns look wrong.
#>

[CmdletBinding()]
param(
    [string]$RootFolder       = "C:\CyberArkReports",
    [int]   $PageSize         = 100,
    [int]   $MaxRetries       = 3,
    [int]   $RetryWaitSeconds = 5
)

